article.headline: Five Suns score in double figures
article.linkText: Suns hand Grizzlies fourth loss in five games
article.story: PHOENIX (AP) -- The young and inexperienced Phoenix Suns are finding satisfaction in their improved play. Amare Stoudemire scored 23 of his 29 points in the first half and the Suns handed the undermanned Memphis Grizzlies their fourth loss in five games, 89-83 Sunday night. "We're playing hard and strong from the beginning, and we're learning how to close games," Stoudemire said. "We're playing tenacious defense, crashing the boards. That's what it takes to beat an elite team. All those experiences are going to benefit us for next season." The victory marked the first time this season that the Suns had beaten two over-.500 teams in a row. Phoenix defeated Sacramento on Friday night. The loss left the Grizzlies in a fifth-place tie with Dallas in the Western Conference. The Mavericks lost 109-107 at Golden State Sunday night. The Grizzlies and Mavericks meet Tuesday night at Dallas. "I want to win, regardless of what the future holds, and I want to win right now," Stoudemire added, dismissing the Suns' status as a draft lottery team because of their dismal 28-52 record. Leandro Barbosa added 17 points for the Suns, who are 16-2 at home against Memphis. Joe Johnson scored 15, and Shawn Marion and Casey Jacobsen had 10 apiece. Antonio McDyess contributed 13 rebounds, Marion had 10 boards and Stoudemire eight. Suns coach Mike D'Antoni enjoyed Stoudemire's overall performance. "Amare was a beast again," D'Antoni said, especially getting to the foul line. That puts a lot of pressure on other teams." Stoudemire hit 13 of 16 free throws. Memphis coach Hubie Brown praised both Stoudemire and Barbosa. "Stoudemire had a monster first half, absolutely terrific," he said. "He broke our guys down. "Barbosa played great in the fourth quarter. He was able to beast our guys off the dribble, go to the basket and make something happen. He was very instrumental for them." Shane Battier led the Grizzlies with 18 points, James Posey had 16 and Stromile Swift scored 13 and grabbed 10 rebounds. The Grizzlies were without forward Pau Gasol, their leading scorer and rebounder, and reserve swingman Bonzi Wells, their third-leading scorer. Gasol was out with a sore right foot and Wells was sidelined with back spasms. In addition, Posey, who was averaging 26.8 points in his last six games, was slowed by a hip injury and picked up three personal fouls in the first 14 minutes. Stoudemire was dominant in the first half as the Suns built a 49-39 lead. The only thing that appeared to stop him was foul trouble. He collected two personals in the first quarter and sat out the final two minutes, incurred his third foul in the final minute of the second period and picked up No. 4 with less than four minutes gone in the third quarter and again went to the bench for the remainder of the period. In the first half, Stoudemire hit six of eight field goals and 11 of 13 foul shots while also grabbing six rebounds. Battier, with 12 points in the half, and Swift, with 10 points starting in place of Gasol, kept the Grizzlies in contention. Memphis hit the offensive boards hard and took 48 shots in the half, 20 more than Phoenix, but made only 15, the same as the Suns. The Suns, meanwhile, made 19 of 22 foul shots to seven of nine for the Grizzlies. The Suns led 26-20 after one period and increased their lead to 10 points by halftime despite committing 11 turnovers in the second period. Phoenix padded its lead 65-51 in the third quarter, but the Grizzlies scored the final seven points of the period and trailed by only seven going into the final 12 minutes. Johnson played 46 minutes, the 33rd consecutive game he has played 40 minutes or more, the 13th-longest streak in NBA history. Just ahead of him are Wilt Chamberlain and Neil Johnston, each with 34 straight games of at least 40 minutes.< ^Notes@: Chamberlain has the record of 102 consecutive 40-minute games (twice). ... Johnson scored in double figures for the 42nd consecutive game, the fifth-best streak in the league. ... The Grizzlies' Jake Tsakaladis and the Suns' Donnell Harvey got into a brief skirmish in the first minute of the second quarter and both were assessed technical fouls. A minute later, Harvey was charged with a flagrant foul against Posey.
